   "trap": "- (1) CRAO is a **STROKE OF THE EYE** — a retinal infarct; manage on the **acute stroke pathway**, not as 'just' an eye problem\n  - Most tempting wrong move: treating it as routine ophthalmology and **missing the urgent neuro/carotid/cardiac workup**\n- (2) Retina tolerates ischaemia poorly — irreversible damage by **~4 h**; time is retina/brain\n  - **IV thrombolysis within ~4.5 h** of onset is an emerging treatment via stroke services, evidence mixed, NOT yet routine standard everywhere — contested/centre-dependent\n- (3) Bedside **'eyeball-lowering' measures** (ocular massage, anterior-chamber paracentesis, CO2 rebreathing, IOP-lowering) have **weak evidence** but are sometimes tried while organising transfer\n- (4) ALWAYS exclude **GIANT CELL ARTERITIS** in anyone ≥50 (check ESR/CRP, ask jaw claudication/scalp tenderness)\n  - **Arteritic CRAO needs immediate high-dose steroid** to save the fellow eye",
