   "topic": "Keratitis / corneal ulcer in a contact-lens wearer — the can't-miss bug and the steroid/no-patch gotchas",
   "subarea": "Red eye & acute vision loss",
   "trap": "- The feared organism in contact-lens-related microbial keratitis is **Pseudomonas aeruginosa**\n  - Rapidly destructive, can **perforate the cornea within 24–48 h**\n  - **Overnight soft-lens wear** is the key risk factor\n  - CL wear causes ~**80–90%** of Australian microbial keratitis\n- **Acanthamoeba** (~5% of CL infections) — suspect with:\n  - Pain **disproportionate to signs**\n  - Ring infiltrate\n  - History of swimming/showering/topping-up solution in lenses\n  - Classic **delayed-diagnosis trap**\n- **NEVER patch** a contact-lens ulcer\n- **NEVER start topical steroid** before infection cleared/microbiology back\n- Any CL wearer with a suspected corneal infiltrate = **same-day ophthalmology** for corneal scrape (MC&S) BEFORE antibiotics where feasible\n  - Then intensive **fluoroquinolone** (e.g. ofloxacin/ciprofloxacin) hourly including overnight\n- Stop lens wear; bring the **lenses + case + solution** for culture",
   "whatFirst": "- **Same-day ophthalmology**\n- Corneal scrape for **microscopy and culture** (plus lens/case/solution) BEFORE starting drops if feasible\n- Intensive topical **fluoroquinolone monotherapy** (e.g. ofloxacin 0.3% or ciprofloxacin) **hourly day and night** initially\n- **Cycloplegic** for comfort\n- Do **NOT patch**, do NOT use steroid, do NOT give steroid/antibiotic combo drop empirically",
   "discriminator": "- vs **HSV epithelial keratitis**: HSV gives a branching **DENDRITE** with terminal bulbs (fluorescein), reduced corneal sensation, NO contact-lens link — treat with topical/oral aciclovir, NOT steroid\n- vs **simple conjunctivitis**: keratitis has a focal corneal **infiltrate/staining defect** with pain/photophobia + reduced vision; conjunctivitis cornea is clear, vision normal\n- vs **corneal abrasion**: abrasion is a clean epithelial defect without a **white stromal infiltrate**",
   "redFlags": "- **Central ulcer**, large/enlarging infiltrate (**>1 mm**), hypopyon, pain out of proportion (Acanthamoeba), corneal thinning/descemetocele, any drop in vision → admit/urgent ophthalmology\n- **Pseudomonas** can perforate within **24–48 h**",
   "mcqTrap": "- '**Prescribe chloramphenicol and review in 48 hours**' or '**apply an eye pad**' in a CL wearer with corneal infiltrate — wrong\n  - Delays scrape/specialist care; patching/under-dosing risks rapid Pseudomonas perforation\n- '**Topical aciclovir**' when there is no dendrite (that's for HSV)",
   "mnemonic": "Contact-lens keratitis = 'Pseudomonas perforates'; pain-out-of-proportion + water exposure = 'Acanthamoeba'. Management: 'No Patch, No Steroid, Scrape then Soak (hourly drops)'.",
   "viva": "- State: 'Contact-lens wearer with a painful red eye and a corneal infiltrate is **microbial keratitis until proven otherwise**'\n  - **Pseudomonas** can perforate within a day\n- Stop lens wear, refer **same-day** for a corneal scrape before intensive **hourly fluoroquinolone**\n- Would **NOT patch** or use steroids\n- Examiner probes the **Acanthamoeba pain-out-of-proportion clue** and why no steroid/no patch",
   "source": "eTG (Therapeutic Guidelines, Eye — microbial keratitis); Carnt et al., Clin Exp Optom 2017 'The diagnosis and management of contact lens-related microbial keratitis' (scrape, hourly fluoroquinolone, no patch/no steroid); Stapleton et al., Clin Exp Optom 2020 'Contact lens-related corneal infection in Australia' (Pseudomonas/Acanthamoeba predominance). Pseudomonas/Acanthamoeba predominance and CL wear ~80–90% of AU microbial keratitis confirmed this run.",
   "verified": true,
