   "topic": "Optic neuritis — the painful-loss, MS-link and 'don't-steroid-orally' gotchas",
   "subarea": "Red eye & acute vision loss",
   "trap": "- **Pain on eye movement** + colour desaturation distinguishes ON from painless vascular causes (CRAO/CRVO)\n- It is the presenting feature of **MS** in many — MRI brain/orbits with contrast risk-stratifies conversion\n  - Also screens for **NMOSD/MOGAD**, which behave differently and need aggressive treatment\n- Treatment trap (**ONTT**): oral prednisolone ALONE **doubles the recurrence rate** (~30% vs ~14–16%) and is NOT recommended\n  - If treating to speed recovery: use **IV methylprednisolone** (then taper)\n  - Steroids hasten recovery WITHOUT changing **final visual outcome**\n  - Many mild cases are **observed**\n- Atypical features (bilateral, no pain, no recovery, severe, older patient, optic atrophy) → think **NMOSD/MOGAD/compressive/infective**, not typical demyelinating ON",
   "whatFirst": "- Confirm clinically: **acuity, colour vision, RAPD, fields, fundoscopy**\n- Urgent **neuro-ophthalmology/neurology referral** + MRI brain and orbits with gadolinium\n- Consider **aquaporin-4 (NMO) and MOG antibodies** if atypical/bilateral/severe\n- If treating: **IV methylprednisolone** (not oral prednisolone alone)\n- **Exclude GCA** in older patients",
   "discriminator": "- vs **CRAO/CRVO**: ON is PAINFUL on movement with marked **colour desaturation** and often a normal disc; vascular causes are painless\n- vs **papilloedema**: papilloedema is BILATERAL disc swelling with preserved acuity early and **no RAPD**; ON is usually unilateral with reduced acuity + RAPD\n- vs **AION (incl. arteritic)**: AION is painless **altitudinal loss** in older patients with a swollen pale disc — check ESR/CRP for GCA",
   "redFlags": "- **Bilateral**, no pain, no recovery by ~2 weeks, severe/very poor acuity, **age >50**, or optic atrophy → atypical\n  - Investigate for **NMOSD/MOGAD**, compression, infection (syphilis, TB), GCA\n  - Atypical ON can **blind permanently** if NMOSD missed",
   "mcqTrap": "- '**Treat with a course of oral prednisolone**' — wrong: per the ONTT, oral prednisolone alone **increased recurrence**\n  - Use **IV methylprednisolone** if treating\n  - Steroids speed recovery but **don't change final acuity**\n- Attributing painful unilateral loss to **migraine** and skipping the MRI/MS workup",
   "mnemonic": "'Pain on movement + Poor colour = optic Neuritis' (3 P's). Treatment: 'IV yes, oral-only no' (ONTT).",
   "viva": "- State: 'Subacute painful monocular loss with red desaturation and an afferent defect is **optic neuritis** until proven otherwise'\n- Arrange **MRI brain and orbits with contrast** for MS risk and to screen for NMO/MOG\n- If treating: **IV methylprednisolone**, not oral prednisolone alone\n  - Steroids speed recovery without changing **final outcome**\n- Examiner probes the **ONTT steroid rule** and **atypical-feature flags**",
   "source": "Optic Neuritis Treatment Trial (ONTT; NEJM 1992 + long-term follow-up) — oral prednisone alone doubled recurrence (~30% vs ~14–16% IV/placebo); IV methylprednisolone 1 g/day x3 hastens recovery without changing final acuity. Australian neuro-ophthalmology practice / eTG; MS, NMOSD, MOGAD antibody testing for atypical cases. ONTT recurrence and recovery figures confirmed this run.",
