   "topic": "Papilloedema & idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH) — the 'image-before-LP' and opening-pressure gotchas",
   "subarea": "Red eye & acute vision loss",
   "trap": "- **NEVER do the lumbar puncture first** — neuroimage (MRI brain + MR venography) BEFORE LP\n  - LP into a mass lesion risks **coning**\n- Diagnostic number for IIH: CSF opening pressure **>25 cmH2O** in the lateral decubitus position\n  - **25–30** is a grey zone\n  - Must have normal CSF composition and normal/specific imaging (modified Dandy criteria)\n- Demographic trap: classically an **obese woman of childbearing age**\n- Drug triggers — **tetracyclines** (doxycycline/minocycline), **vitamin A/retinoids/isotretinoin** — stopping the offending drug is part of management\n- Symptoms: headache worse lying/Valsalva, **transient visual obscurations**, pulsatile tinnitus, diplopia from a non-localising **CN VI palsy**\n- Treatment: **weight loss + acetazolamide**\n  - Fulminant/failing vision → urgent surgery: **optic nerve sheath fenestration** or CSF shunt\n  - The threat is **permanent vision loss**, not headache",
   "whatFirst": "- Confirm bilateral disc swelling, check **fields and acuity**\n- **URGENT MRI brain + MRV** (exclude mass and venous sinus thrombosis) BEFORE LP\n- Then LP for **opening pressure (>25 cmH2O)** and normal CSF analysis\n- Stop causative drugs (**tetracyclines, vitamin A/retinoids**)\n- Start **acetazolamide + weight loss**; involve neurology + ophthalmology; serial visual fields\n- Fulminant vision loss → **urgent surgical decompression**",
   "discriminator": "- vs **papillitis (anterior optic neuritis)**: papillitis is UNILATERAL with reduced acuity, pain on movement, RAPD; papilloedema is **BILATERAL** with preserved acuity early and NO RAPD\n- vs **pseudopapilloedema (optic disc drusen)**: no obscured vessels, no hyperaemia, **autofluorescent drusen** on imaging, normal fields\n- vs **malignant hypertension**: check BP — severe hypertension causes bilateral disc swelling too",
   "redFlags": "- Rapidly worsening **fields/acuity**, fulminant IIH, CN VI palsy, or imaging suggesting **venous sinus thrombosis** → urgent neurology/neurosurgery\n- ANY new bilateral disc swelling = exclude **space-occupying lesion and CVST** first\n- Check **BP** to exclude malignant hypertension",
   "mcqTrap": "- '**Perform lumbar puncture**' as the immediate next step — wrong: you must **IMAGE first** (MRI + MRV) to exclude a mass or sinus thrombosis before LP\n- Forgetting the **drug history** (tetracyclines/vitamin A)\n- Treating as benign because headache seems mild — the real danger is **silent progressive vision loss**",
   "mnemonic": "'Image before you needle' (MRI/MRV before LP). IIH triggers = 'Tetracyclines, vitamin A/retinoids, Obesity'. Opening-pressure cut-off: 'over 25 = IIH'.",
   "viva": "- State: 'Bilateral disc swelling means **raised intracranial pressure** until proven otherwise'\n- **Image first** with MRI and MR venography to exclude mass and venous sinus thrombosis BEFORE LP\n  - LP shows opening pressure **above 25 cm of water** with normal CSF in IIH\n- Stop any **tetracycline or vitamin A**, start **acetazolamide and weight loss**\n- Monitor fields because the real risk is **permanent vision loss**\n- Examiner probes the **image-before-LP rule** and the **opening-pressure number**",
   "source": "Modified Dandy / Friedman revised diagnostic criteria for IIH (CSF opening pressure >25 cmH2O, normal CSF, normal or specific neuroimaging); Australian neurology practice — image (MRI+MRV) before LP, acetazolamide + weight loss, drug triggers. Opening pressure >25 cmH2O, MRI+MRV-before-LP, and acetazolamide first-line confirmed this run.",
