   "topic": "Retinal detachment — the flashes/floaters triage and macula-on/off timing gotchas",
   "subarea": "Red eye & acute vision loss",
   "trap": "- New flashes + floaters = **posterior vitreous detachment** until proven otherwise\n  - Demands **same-day/urgent dilated fundus exam** to look for a retinal tear BEFORE it progresses to detachment\n  - Early **laser/cryo to a tear** prevents detachment\n- The surgical-urgency discriminator is **macula-ON vs macula-OFF**:\n  - **Macula-ON** (fovea attached, central vision preserved) = more urgent repair (ideally within **~24 h**) to save central vision\n  - Once **macula-OFF** the central-vision window is partly lost — do NOT let a macula-on detachment wait\n- Risk factors: **myopia**, prior cataract surgery, trauma, lattice degeneration\n- **Tractional detachment** in proliferative diabetic retinopathy is a different mechanism\n- An **RAPD** suggests a large/macula-off detachment",
   "whatFirst": "- **Urgent (same-day) ophthalmology** with DILATED fundoscopy to find a tear/detachment\n- Determine **macula-on vs macula-off** (central acuity)\n- Tear without detachment → **laser retinopexy/cryotherapy**\n- Detachment → surgical repair (pneumatic retinopexy, scleral buckle, or vitrectomy)\n  - **Macula-on** = expedite within **~24 h**\n- Posture advice as directed",
   "discriminator": "- vs **vitreous haemorrhage**: VH gives sudden floaters/'cobwebs'/red haze and **loss of red reflex**/fundus view — common in proliferative diabetic retinopathy or a torn vessel from PVD; both need urgent dilated exam\n- vs **migraine aura**: bilateral homonymous **scintillating zigzags** lasting ~20–30 min with headache, fully resolving — not a curtain or persistent floaters\n- vs **CRAO/CRVO**: those are vascular, no flashes/curtain",
   "redFlags": "- A **'curtain'/field defect** (= detachment has occurred), sudden many new floaters, loss of central vision (macula threatened/off), RAPD → urgent same-day ophthalmology\n- **Macula-ON detachment** = time-critical surgical emergency to save central vision",
   "mcqTrap": "- '**Reassure — floaters are benign** and review in 6 weeks' in a patient with new flashes and floaters — wrong: new symptoms mandate **same-day dilated exam** to exclude a tear/detachment\n- Treating a **macula-on detachment** as semi-elective (it is more urgent than macula-off for preserving central vision)",
   "mnemonic": "'Flashes, Floaters, Field-loss (curtain)' = the RD triad. 'Macula-on = clock's ON — fix in 24 h'.",
   "viva": "- State: 'New flashes and a shower of floaters with a descending curtain is a **retinal detachment** until proven otherwise'\n  - Refer **same-day** for dilated fundoscopy\n- The key question is **macula-on or macula-off**\n  - Macula-on = more **time-critical repair, ideally within 24 hours**, to save central vision\n- Examiner probes the **PVD-to-tear-to-detachment sequence** and the **macula-on urgency**",
   "source": "RANZCO acute floaters-and-flashes / retinal detachment patient guidance + standard Australian vitreoretinal practice. Macula-on urgency (fovea-attachment is the strongest predictor of final acuity; repair within ~24 h) and same-day dilated exam for new PVD symptoms confirmed against vitreoretinal literature (EyeWiki/AAO) this run.",
