   "trap": "- Management is **topical, not oral**\n  - Oral antibiotics do NOT penetrate the canal adequately\n  - Reserved for: spreading **cellulitis beyond the canal**, systemic illness, or immunocompromise/diabetic\n- First-line: **aural toilet** (clean the canal) + topical combination drops (e.g. dexamethasone + framycetin + gramicidin, or ciprofloxacin-based) +/- a wick if canal too swollen\n- Critical catch: if the TM is **PERFORATED**, avoid **aminoglycoside-containing drops** (framycetin/neomycin = ototoxic, contraindicated with perforation)\n  - Use a **quinolone (ciprofloxacin)** instead",
   "whatFirst": "- **Aural toilet/microsuction** to clear debris so topical agents reach the canal\n- Insert a **wick** if canal is occluded by oedema",
   "discriminator": "- **Otitis externa**: pain on tragal pressure/pinna traction, canal swollen + discharging, hearing usually preserved\n- **AOM**: deep pain, bulging TM, no tragal tenderness\n- **Fungal OE (otomycosis)**: often after prolonged antibiotic drops; itch + visible **fungal hyphae/spores** → antifungal drops, not antibacterial",
   "redFlags": "- **Malignant (necrotising) otitis externa**: elderly **DIABETIC** or immunocompromised\n  - Severe deep pain **out of proportion**\n  - Granulation tissue at the **bony-cartilaginous junction** of the canal floor\n  - **Cranial nerve palsy** (esp. CN VII)\n  - Urgent referral, imaging, **IV anti-pseudomonal therapy**\n  - This is the high-yield escalation",
