   "subarea": "ENT acute & head/neck cancer",
   "trap": "- Three things masquerade as 'bad sore throat'; the exam wants the discriminator + management gotcha for each\n- **(1) Bacterial tonsillitis (GAS):** use **Centor/FeverPAIN** to decide testing/antibiotics; most pharyngitis is viral so default is NOT antibiotics\n  - First-line: **phenoxymethylpenicillin (penicillin V)** for a FULL **10 days** (critical for acute rheumatic fever prevention), NOT amoxicillin\n- **(2) Quinsy (peritonsillar abscess):** **trismus** + 'hot-potato' muffled voice + **uvula deviated AWAY** from the affected (swollen) side\n  - Needs **needle aspiration/incision + drainage + antibiotics**, not just oral penicillin\n- **(3) Glandular fever (EBV):** adolescent/young adult, prolonged fever, gross tonsillar exudate, posterior cervical lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly\n  - Classic gotcha: give **amoxicillin/ampicillin** → **florid maculopapular rash**\n  - Advise **NO contact sport** for the splenomegaly period (splenic rupture risk)",
   "whatFirst": "- Tonsillitis: assess **Centor/FeverPAIN** + analgesia; if treating, **penicillin V x 10 days**\n- Quinsy: **drainage (aspiration/I&D) + antibiotics**\n- Glandular fever: **supportive care**, AVOID amoxicillin, advise **contact-sport avoidance**",
   "discriminator": "- **Quinsy:** unilateral, trismus, **uvula deviated to the contralateral (well) side**, hot-potato voice\n- **Glandular fever:** bilateral exudate, **posterior cervical nodes**, splenomegaly, atypical lymphocytes, positive Monospot/EBV serology\n- **GAS tonsillitis:** absence of cough/coryza, tender anterior nodes, exudate, fever (**Centor** criteria)",
