   "subarea": "ENT acute & head/neck cancer",
   "trap": "- The exam wants you to separate **benign peripheral (BPPV)** from **dangerous central (stroke)** at the bedside\n- **BPPV:** brief (<60 s, typically <30 s) positional vertigo\n  - Diagnosed with **DIX-HALLPIKE** (provokes torsional/upbeating nystagmus with LATENCY of a few seconds and FATIGABILITY)\n  - Treated with **EPLEY canalith-repositioning manoeuvre** (NOT medications, which just mask it)\n- **Central gotcha — HINTS:** counter-intuitively, a **NORMAL head-impulse test** (no corrective saccade) in someone with acute spontaneous vertigo and nystagmus suggests a **CENTRAL/stroke cause**\n  - HINTS = Head Impulse Normal, Test of Skew present, direction-changing/vertical Nystagmus\n- **Direction-changing or vertical/pure-torsional nystagmus**, inability to walk, and other neurology = central until proven otherwise",
   "whatFirst": "- Positional/brief vertigo: do **Dix-Hallpike**; if positive, perform **Epley**\n- Acute spontaneous continuous vertigo: do **HINTS** + full neuro exam to exclude central cause",
   "discriminator": "- **BPPV (peripheral):** brief, positional; latency + fatigable torsional/upbeat nystagmus on Dix-Hallpike; **ABNORMAL head impulse** (corrective saccade); unidirectional nystagmus; can walk\n- **Central:** persistent; **NORMAL head impulse test**; direction-changing or **vertical nystagmus**; skew deviation; severe gait ataxia; other brainstem/cerebellar signs",
   "redFlags": "- **Normal head impulse** in acute continuous vertigo (HINTS central)\n- **Skew deviation**\n- **Direction-changing or vertical nystagmus**\n- **Inability to stand/walk**\n- Headache/neck pain\n- **Focal neurology**\n- **New deafness with vertigo**\n  - All: urgent imaging (**MRI** better than CT for posterior fossa)/stroke pathway",
